    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Great question! The interest rate on an ARM can indeed fluctuate, but most lenders cap how much it can rise in any given adjustment period. You’ll typically see a “margin” added to the base rate, plus an “index” (like the Prime Rate or SOFR) that moves with the market. The total increase is usually limited by the loan’s “adjustment cap” — often set at 2% to 3% per year, though some loans allow a higher “lifetime cap” that prevents the rate from ever exceeding a certain percentage.\n\nFor example, if your ARM starts at 3.5% and the index rises 0.5% in year 2, your rate might jump to 4.0%, and then to 4.5% in year 3, and so on. The monthly payment will change accordingly, but the cap ensures it won’t skyrocket unexpectedly. You can ask your lender for the specific adjustment schedule and caps so you can see exactly how your payment might evolve over the first five years.",
      "source": "target",
